            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mark Washington\u2019s quiet empathy was forged in the industrial flatlands of Ohio, where emotions were often buried under a layer of stoicism. The son of a factory worker and a secretary, he grew up in a household where problems were endured, not discussed. This changed when his younger sister developed a severe eating disorder in her teens. Watching his family struggle, feeling utterly helpless, Mark found his calling. He enrolled in a state university, earning a Bachelor's in Social Work, driven by a newfound need to give others the language and support his own family lacked.\n\nDrawn to its reputation for progressive values and social acceptance, he moved to San Francisco in the early 1990s to pursue his Master of Social Work. He arrived directly into the cauldron of the AIDS crisis. The experience was harrowing and transformative. He volunteered at hospices and support groups, witnessing profound loss but also extraordinary community resilience. This crucible Vcemented his commitment to the field, and after earning his LCSW, he dedicated his career to public service, eventually finding his niche as a high school social worker.\n\nNow 53, Mark is a fixture at a large San Francisco public high school. His daily routine begins with a ride on the N Judah MUNI line from his quiet Inner Sunset apartment. He spends his days navigating the turbulent inner worlds of teenagers, offering a steady, non-judgmental presence amidst academic pressure, family drama, and identity crises. His $145,000 salary feels less like a measure of success and more like a symbol of stability earned after decades of demanding work.\n\nMark has remained single since losing his partner in the late \u201890s, but his life is rich with connection. His \"found family\" consists of a tight-knit group of friends, many of whom also weathered the city\u2019s most challenging years. Having seen San Francisco through its booms and busts, he feels a deep, protective love for its gritty, compassionate soul. His dream isn't a dramatic life change, but a gentle downshift: retiring in the next decade to mentor new social workers and finally have the time to learn pottery, a quiet, tactile craft to soothe a mind long dedicated to others."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the cold glass of the living room window against his forehead in Ohio, sometime around 1985. It was late, and he\u2019d found his younger sister not crying, but silently tracing the outline of her own sharp collarbone in the darkened reflection. He didn't speak, just felt a profound, aching helplessness that galvanized into a quiet resolve. It wasn't about having answers, he realized then, but about creating a space where the unspeakable could finally be whispered aloud. That moment set the coordinates for his entire life.\n\n2.\nSan Francisco, 1992. He was volunteering at a hospice South of Market, sitting with a man named Robert who was impossibly thin and frail. Robert couldn\u2019t eat, but he vividly described the taste of a perfect cioppino from a North Beach restaurant, his eyes alight for a full minute. Mark just listened, holding a cool cloth to Robert\u2019s brow. He felt the city\u2019s immense grief as a physical weight, but also saw how dignity could be found in the memory of a good meal. It taught him that his job was simply to bear witness.\n\n3.\nIt was the sound of the N Judah\u2019s bell in the late \u201890s that broke him. His partner, Miguel, had died in their Inner Sunset apartment just two days before. Mark stood by the window, watching the fog swallow the streetlights, and the familiar clang of the approaching train felt impossibly normal, an affront to the stillness in his home. The grief was solitary yet public, merging with the ghosts of a decade. That sound forever entwined his deepest personal loss with the city\u2019s melancholic, resilient heartbeat.\n\n4.\nAround 2011, a perpetually angry junior was sent to his office for the tenth time. The boy stared at the floor, fists clenched, radiating fury. Instead of another lecture, Mark just waited in silence. After ten minutes, the boy\u2019s shoulders slumped and he whispered, \"My mom's gone.\" Mark didn't fix it, but he sat in that painful silence with him. In that moment, he felt he had finally become the adult his own family had needed\u2014a steady, non-judgmental anchor in an impossible storm.\n\n5.\nJust last spring, riding the N Judah home, he watched a pack of high schoolers\u2014not from his school, just kids\u2014laughing, sharing earbuds, and complaining about homework. As the train emerged from the tunnel and the late sun lit up the avenues of the Sunset, he felt a wave of quiet, protective love. He had weathered the city\u2019s crises and tended to its youth. He saw the future in their loud, vibrant energy, and for the first time, pictured his own: quiet hands, spinning clay, finally at peace."
